      "seed": 1055613560,
      "version": 271,
      "versionNonce": 171337135,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1769938907660,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep Dives\n1. Reserve tickets - this was metioned in handling contention, where instead of locking the rows of the isolation level things we could use this method, let\nsee what it is.\n2. I hope i get Nupur",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep Dives\n1. Reserve tickets - this was metioned in handling contention, where instead of locking the rows of the isolation level things we could use this method, let\nsee what it is.\n2. I hope i get Nupur",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "azMXZcX4gFpo0cq8qxBEl",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 102.90594482421875,
      "y": 2818.322265625,
      "width": 1561.9591064453125,
      "height": 675,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b08",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1285918034,
      "version": 2272,
      "versionNonce": 724227410,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1769940208307,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Scaling Read\n\n1. Optimize db\n2. Horizontally Scale\n3. Add external Caching\n\nExplanation\n1. Optimize DB:\n   \na. one way is to vertically scale the db, modern cloud providers provide very powerful machines, 128 GB of RAM, 16 TB HDD.... something of that sort.\n    first aim is always to use this fully.\nb. Indexing: adding indexes to the columns will help us do away with full table scans and this dramatically improves perfomance in case of a big data set.\n    Indexing is like adding a lookup table which decreases the time complexity from O(n) to O(logn).\n    Indexes are mostly B-Trees, but there are other sort of indexes too for different other purposes, like one is there for exact lookups, other is there\n    for columns requiring range based searching\n\n2. Horizontally Scale: There is a limit to the amount of data one single db server can hold, so when we start reaching that limit, it is better to break the \n    db (shard the db). Few ways of sharding, functional shard, vertical shard, and the most vital part here is to take care about the key we are using to shard\n    our db, if the key is not helping out in distributing the data uniformly, we again will run into a db shard overloaded and choking, thus it becomes important\n    to have the correct choice of key.\n\n3. Db sharding suits scaling our writes better, it should be our last resort while scaling the writes, we should first think about adding an external caching\n    layer to reduce the load on our db and start serving the frequently accessed data directly from the cache.\n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Scaling Read\n\n1. Optimize db\n2. Horizontally Scale\n3. Add external Caching\n\nExplanation\n1. Optimize DB:\n   \na. one way is to vertically scale the db, modern cloud providers provide very powerful machines, 128 GB of RAM, 16 TB HDD.... something of that sort.\n    first aim is always to use this fully.\nb. Indexing: adding indexes to the columns will help us do away with full table scans and this dramatically improves perfomance in case of a big data set.\n    Indexing is like adding a lookup table which decreases the time complexity from O(n) to O(logn).\n    Indexes are mostly B-Trees, but there are other sort of indexes too for different other purposes, like one is there for exact lookups, other is there\n    for columns requiring range based searching\n\n2. Horizontally Scale: There is a limit to the amount of data one single db server can hold, so when we start reaching that limit, it is better to break the \n    db (shard the db). Few ways of sharding, functional shard, vertical shard, and the most vital part here is to take care about the key we are using to shard\n    our db, if the key is not helping out in distributing the data uniformly, we again will run into a db shard overloaded and choking, thus it becomes important\n    to have the correct choice of key.\n\n3. Db sharding suits scaling our writes better, it should be our last resort while scaling the writes, we should first think about adding an external caching\n    layer to reduce the load on our db and start serving the frequently accessed data directly from the cache.\n\n\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Xw78otEsnzd02ZV3ZEpyY",
